First off, you'll need to set up your project. Let's call it `RoomMaster`. Open your terminal and type:
```
npx create-react-app RoomMaster
cd RoomMaster
npm install express mongoose body-parser cors
```

Now, let's start with the backend. Create a file named `server.js` in a new folder called `backend`.

In `server.js`, you'll want something like this:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const cors = require('cors');

const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json());
app.use(cors());

// Mock data for now
let rooms = [
    { id: 1, name: "Conference Room", capacity: 50 },
    { id: 2, name: "Meeting Room", capacity: 30 }
];

app.get('/rooms', (req, res) => {
    res.send(rooms);
});

app.post('/rooms', (req, res) => {
    const newRoom = req.body;
    rooms.push(newRoom);
    res.send({ message: 'Room added' });
});

app.listen(5000, () => console.log('Server running on port 5000'));
```

On the frontend, in your React app, you can create a simple component to fetch and display rooms:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function RoomList() {
    const [rooms, setRooms] = useState([]);

    useEffect(() => {
        fetch('http://localhost:5000/rooms')
            .then(res => res.json())
            .then(data => setRooms(data));
    }, []);

    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Room List</h1>
            <ul>
                {rooms.map(room => (
                    <li key={room.id}>{room.name} - Capacity: {room.capacity}</li>
                ))}
            </ul>
        </div>
    );
}

export default RoomList;
```

Remember to replace the mock data with actual database interactions using MongoDB and Mongoose. And don't forget to handle more complex operations like updating and deleting rooms.

This is just the tip of the iceberg, but hey, it's a start! Good luck with your room management system. You're welcome.

