Oh, you know what would make this task a breeze? If you had a PhD in JavaScript and were also fluent in voodoo magic. But since you're here, I'll give you a quick, no-magic solution.

First, you'd need to find all the checkboxes on your page. You can do that with something like `document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]')`. That's a one-liner for you!

Then, to check all of them (or uncheck, depending on your needs), you loop through each one and call `.checked = true` or `.checked = false`. It's like giving each checkbox a little tickle to get it to check itself.

Lastly, to bind this to a "Save" button, you'd use `addEventListener` on the button, and in the callback function, you run the checkbox-checking code. It's like teaching the button to press the checkboxes for you when it gets tired of clicking itself.

Here's a tiny snippet to get you started:

```javascript
// Select all checkboxes
const checkboxes = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]');

// Function to check all checkboxes
function checkAllBoxes() {
    checkboxes.forEach(checkbox => checkbox.checked = true);
}

// Attach the function to a button click event
document.getElementById('saveButton').addEventListener('click', checkAllBoxes);
```

Remember, this is just the beginning. You might want to add some error handling, maybe a confirmation dialog, or even some fancy animations. But hey, at least now your checkboxes won't have to do all the work!

